data.text: A global pandemic was never going to be easy to weather, but so much of what we are experiencing is totally avoidable with better management from government.

data.text: This is just what’s happening in my part of the world. All of this is mirrored across the rest of the live events and entertainment industry. And countless other industries too, I'm sure.

data.text:
Some things have changed. 

Lifetime savings, and savings for deposits on houses have been eviscerated. 

Mental health has plummeted. 

Tens of thousands of full-timers have lots their jobs.

data.text:
In some respects things haven’t changed much since June.

Hundreds of thousands of theatre workers are still out of work. 

Hundreds of thousands have still had little to no support from the government.

data.text:
But I do consider myself lucky to earn 17% of my normal income, because many can not pivot into another industry.

I also typically employ about 10 to 15 subcontractors each year for various projects. None of those could happen this year.

data.text: I’m lucky to have transferable skills so could pivot into more online & broadcast work. But even working almost non-stop my income is down 83% for this financial year. And that’s before I pay taxes and cover my expenses. Unlikely to put anything towards pension this year.

data.text: The Gov only expects 12.5% of CRF grants to reach  freelancers. The Arts Council has only reached 4% of the freelance workforce with other emergency funds. Venues who’ve received a CRF grant can’t put on shows because we’re in a lockdown, so they can’t employ freelancers.

text: The Gov only expects 12.5% of CRF grants to reach  freelancers. The Arts Council has only reached 4% of the freelance workforce with other emergency funds. Venues who’ve received a CRF grant can’t put on shows because we’re in a lockdown, so they can’t employ freelancers.

data.text: In good news, the government brought in the Cultural Recovery Fund in July, worth £1.57billion. 7.9% of that has gone to the theatre industry which has provided a bunch of venues & companies with a real lifeline.

text: In good news, the government brought in the Cultural Recovery Fund in July, worth £1.57billion. 7.9% of that has gone to the theatre industry which has provided a bunch of venues & companies with a real lifeline.

data.text: The government brought in the Self-Employed Income Support Scheme, but with harsh limitations. 33% of our workforce has had no support since March 2020. The next 46% got less than £600 - in total - to get through 9 months without work. Only 21% has got more than £600 in support.

text: The government brought in the Self-Employed Income Support Scheme, but with harsh limitations. 33% of our workforce has had no support since March 2020. The next 46% got less than £600 - in total - to get through 9 months without work. Only 21% has got more than £600 in support.

data.text: But the main hit has been to the freelance workforce, which is about 70-80% of the industry. You won’t see news stories about the massive swathes of job losses here because they’re essentially invisible. Freelancers don’t get made redundant - they just stop getting new work.

text: But the main hit has been to the freelance workforce, which is about 70-80% of the industry. You won’t see news stories about the massive swathes of job losses here because they’re essentially invisible. Freelancers don’t get made redundant - they just stop getting new work.

data.text: Many theatres & support companies have had to make large proportions of their full-time & casual workforce redundant despite the furlough scheme. Some have just gone bankrupt.

text: Many theatres & support companies have had to make large proportions of their full-time & casual workforce redundant despite the furlough scheme. Some have just gone bankrupt.

data.text: There is a lot that is beyond all our control. But how well the crisis is managed, and the impact it has on our industries & workforces is more within our control. Or more to the point, it is within the control of our government.

text: There is a lot that is beyond all our control. But how well the crisis is managed, and the impact it has on our industries & workforces is more within our control. Or more to the point, it is within the control of our government.

data.text: To be clear, I am not anti-lockdown. This is a health crisis: lockdowns, masks, testing, vaccines are the only way we will navigate this.

data.text: The Gov announced Operation Sleeping Beauty in Sep to get live events happening by Xmas. Many already-struggling companies innovated & invested to open socially distanced shows. As the country went into Tier 5 these shut down before they could begin to recoup their costs.
